\f0\b\fs36 \cf0 \strokec2 ME\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f3\b0\fs24 \cf0 We live in the Desire Economy. Everything from our ads to our algorithms has one aim: stir appetite. Tap the screen and a new face, a new body, a new fantasy appears\'97on demand, on loop, and on your terms. None of this technology is \'93evil\'94 by itself. It connects people, delivers teaching, and can serve the gospel beautifully. But just beneath the highlights and heart-reactions swims a hungry thing. Not comparison this time\'97that\'92s envy\'92s current. This one slithers in the dark and whispers, 
\f1\i \'93Just a look\'85 just this once.\'94
\f3\i0  It\'92s the alligator of 
\f0\b lust
\f3\b0 .\
Lust promises a rush and delivers a rut. It turns people into pixels, bodies into brands, and desire into a demanding master. And because it thrives in the dark, it convinces you it\'92s harmless as long as no one knows. You don\'92t set out to feed it; you just stop telling it \'93no.\'94\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b \cf0 TRANSITION:
\f3\b0  So how could a few \'93harmless looks,\'94 a flirt-heavy thread, or one more late-night scroll do any real damage? Today isn\'92t about shame; it\'92s about naming. Because what we name, we can tame. And the alligators we refuse to name end up 
\f1\i naming us
\f3\i0 . \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
